# Public Prosecutor _v_ Zhang Rongqi  

### \[2022\] SGDC 188

Criminal Law – Offence – Planning Act (Chapter 232, 1998 Revised Edition) – Carrying out development of land outside a conservation area without planning permission – Total revenue of SGD885,536.33 – Use of 12 dwelling-houses to provide short-term accommodation – Longest duration of offending at 33 months

22 August 2022

### District Judge Brenda Chua:

## Introduction

1       Zhang Rongqi, the accused person, pleaded guilty to nine charges for carrying out development of land outside a conservation area without planning permission under section 12(1) of the Planning Act (Chapter 232, 1998 Revised Edition) punishable under section 12(4)(a) of the Planning Act. There were five charges taken into consideration (“TIC charges”). As the nine proceeded charges were similar, I set out one proceeded charge for reference:

> **URA-000008-2021-1**

> “are charged that you, sometime between 7 Jan 2019 and 6 Jan 2020, did carry out development of the premises known as 218 Pasir Panjang Road #XXX, Singapore 118579 (the “Premises”), which is outside a conservation area, without the planning permission of the Competent Authority, contrary to Section 12(1) of the Planning Act (Cap 232); to wit, by using the Premises which is a dwelling-house to provide short-term accommodation, where the Premises was occupied by the same person(s) for a period of less than 3 consecutive months in return for the payment of rent, which use constitutes development under Section 3(3)(ca) of the said Act, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 12(4)(a) of the Planning Act (Cap 232).”

## Facts

2       The accused admitted to the Statement of Facts without qualification. The Statement of Facts recorded the accused as a 29-year-old male Singapore citizen. Between 2018 to 2020, the accused leased 12 private dwelling-houses from their owners and used them to provide short-term accommodation to guests via Airbnb and Booking.com:

3       Under the Statement of Facts:

> (a)     The accused told the owners (or their sales representatives) that he would reside with his mother and/or his girlfriend at the dwelling-houses;

> (b)     The accused did not obtain the owners’ consent to use their dwelling-houses for the purpose of short-term accommodation;

> (c)     The accused engaged a housekeeper to deal with housekeeping matters and guests;

> (d)     The accused communicated with guests on checking-in and checking-out instructions, as well as to answer queries;

> (e)     The accused told guests not to reveal to anyone that they were renting the dwelling-houses, and to instead tell people that they were residing at a friend’s place;

> (f)     The total revenue deposited in the accused’s bank account was $885,536.33, of which the revenue from Airbnb was $794,620.87 and the revenue from Booking.com was $90,915.46;

> (g)     The total number of deposits, which suggested the frequency of bookings of the dwelling-houses by guests, was 593, of which the deposits from Airbnb was 517 and the deposits from Booking.com was 76; and

> (h)     The accused was working for “Lin Chong” (“Lin”), he did not retain the revenue, and he only received a salary of approximately $3,000 per month for 12 months in 2019.

## The prosecution’s submission on sentence

4       The prosecution relied on the sentencing framework in _Public Prosecutor v Su Jiqing Joel_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGHC 233</span> (“_Joel Su_”) to seek a fine with both a punitive component and a disgorgement component. For the punitive component, the prosecution submitted that the present case fell in the upper end of the slight harm category and the middle of the medium level of culpability category of the _Joel Su_ sentencing matrix, and therefore proposed a fine of between $20,000 to $40,000 per charge:

## Mitigation

7       The accused’s mitigation was made as follows:

> (a)     The accused was a first offender with no antecedents, he pleaded guilty and he came from a humble background;

> (b)     The accused was a pawn used by Lin who instructed him to:

>> (i)       Become the legal tenant on the tenancy agreements;

>> (ii)       Engage a housekeeper to deal with housekeeping matters; and

>> (iii)       Open a bank account which was operated by Lin, who had the bank account token;

> (c)     The accused provided bank statements to the prosecution for tracing the amounts and dwelling-houses involved; and

> (d)     The accused only earned not more than $3,000 per month; he did not make a profit or benefit from the revenue.

8       For the punitive component, the defence sought an amount of $20,000 per charge resulting in a total of $180,000. For the disgorgement component, the defence submitted an amount of $36,000 which was the salary received by the accused. The defence submitted that an overall fine of $216,000 would be of sufficient deterrence.

## The court’s decision

9       The prosecution and the defence relied on the _Joel Su_ case which applied a bifurcated approach to sentencing. For the punitive component of the accused’s sentence, I applied the _Joel Su_ case’s five-step sentencing framework.

### First step – Identify the level of harm and the level of culpability

10     On the level of harm, I considered the number and frequency of bookings as this had a bearing on potential harm and inherently resulted in a loss of privacy for the neighbouring residents and possible safety concerns. I determined this to be in the slight harm category, for the following reasons:

> (a)     The prosecution and the defence did not submit that disamenities were caused; and

> (b)     Even though the number and frequency of bookings were numerous, there was no evidence of tangible or appreciable harm or loss caused.

11     On the level of culpability, I determined that the accused’s culpability was in the medium category, for the following reasons:

> (a)     The accused was motivated by money. It was stated in the mitigation that the accused was enticed by the opportunity and accepted the new job;

> (b)     The offending duration was sustained over the proceeded charges, ranging from about 4.5 months to 33 months;

> (c)     There was a systematic arrangement for concealment. The accused instructed guests to answer queries with lies about residing at a friend’s place, while minimising his interaction with guests by engaging a housekeeper to deal with housekeeping matters; and

> (d)     The scale of the criminal enterprise was sizeable, shown by the total revenue of $885,536.33, the total number of 593 deposits and the number of dwelling-houses involved (namely, 12 in this case).

12     On concealment, taking active steps to avoid detection was regarded as an aggravating factor warranting a more severe sentence (see _Joel Su_ at \[88\]). The rationale was that such offences were difficult to detect. In the Statement of Facts, the accused admitted taking active steps to avoid detection.

### Second step – Identify the applicable indicative sentencing range

13     Using the _Joel Su_ sentencing matrix, the indicative sentencing range for the accused was between $20,000 to $40,000 per proceeded charge.

### Third step – Identify the appropriate starting point within that range

14     Given the duration(s) of offending covered time frames from the shortest period of about 4.5 months to the longest period of about 33 months, the appropriate starting points ranged from $23,000 to $33,000 for each proceeded charge.

### Fourth step – Make adjustments to the starting points to take into account offender-specific factors

15     On offender-specific aggravating factors, the accused had three TIC charges similar to the proceeded charges[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1). Whilst the defence submitted that the accused fully cooperated with the authorities, I agreed with the prosecution that the accused refused to attend before the URA which formed the basis of two other TIC charges.

16     On the offender-specific mitigating factors, I noted the accused’s plea of guilt. I also noted that the accused provided bank statements to facilitate the tracing and tracking of the sums involved for the dwelling-houses.

17     After consideration, I determined the starting points to be a range of $20,000 to $30,000 for each proceeded charge.

### Fifth step – Consider whether the totality principle warrants any final adjustments

18     I considered the totality principle set out in _Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 2 SLR 998</span>. I did not view the sentences as excessive. The multiple charges related to distinct profit-seeking endeavours, with 12 dwelling-houses involving different duration(s) of offending and different revenue streams.

19     For the disgorgement component, I agreed with both the prosecution and the defence to disgorge the accused’s salary of $36,000.

20     Having considered the facts of the case, the prosecution’s submission on sentence and the defence’s submission on mitigation, I imposed the following sentences on the accused:

## Conclusion

21     Accordingly, I imposed a global fine of $241,000 in default 33 weeks’ imprisonment. I calibrated the in-default sentences to ensure that the effect of the total term on the accused was not excessive.
